<paragraph id="574036D4FFE7416ACA81EBE2FE6022CC" blockId="17.[151,1437,439,898]" box="[199,466,654,681]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE7416ACA81EBE2FEFA22CD" bold="true" box="[199,328,654,680]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Reference:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE7416ACB09EBE3FE6022CC" author="Hemp, C." box="[335,466,655,681]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" refId="ref16956" refString="Hemp, C. (2021) A Field Guide to the Bushcrickets, Wetas and Raspy Crickets of Tanzania and Kenya. Senckenberg Gesellschaft fur Naturforschung, Frankfurt, 451 pp." type="book" year="2021">Hemp 2021</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE7416ACA81EBDEFA252294" blockId="17.[151,1437,439,898]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE7416ACA81EBDEFED022A9" bold="true" box="[199,354,690,716]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
The calling song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE7416AC869EBDFFD3722A8" box="[559,645,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1216,1240]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,204,1175]" captionTargetId="figure-23@12.[151,1436,181,1192]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Cosmoderus and Enyaliopsis (figures of E. iaculator based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Cosmoderus femoratus, B Enyaliopsis bloyeti. C Enyaliopsis carolinus, D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus, song type A, E Enyaliopsis spec. 1 (near ephippiatus), song type B, F Enyaliopsis iaculator, G Enyaliopsis jennae, H Enyaliopsis spec. 2 Mpwapwa. Left column overview (5-s-section), right column detail (250-ms-section)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392733/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Fig. 8H</figureCitation>
) consists of long series of syllables (song 
<typeStatus id="88448876FFE7416ACE1EEBDFFB3A22A8" box="[1112,1160,691,717]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">type</typeStatus>
B in 
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE7416ACE84EBDFFAB722A8" box="[1218,1285,690,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1254,1278]" captionTargetBox="[158,1423,198,1221]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[151,1436,181,1231]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Oscillograms of song types in Hetrodini. Song consisting A of long trills (Cosmoderus femoralis CH8627), B of broken trills (including transitions to long echemes; B1 Spalacomimus talpa, B2 Enyaliopsis jennae, B3 Enyaliopsis ephippiatus) or C of regularly repeated echemes (C1 Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus, C2 Eugaster guyoni). 1-min-sections." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392721" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392721/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
; see 
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE7416ACF7CEBDFFA3D22A8" box="[1338,1423,691,717]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,236,476,501]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. Song characteristics of Hetrodini species (for song type see Fig. 5 and text)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" tableUuid="0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190">Table 2</tableCitation>
). The spectrum of the song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE7416ACB85EBBBFDB52294" box="[451,519,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1287,1311]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,201,1247]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Power spectra of male calling songs in Hetrodini species" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392725/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
; peak at 13 kHz) does not show large differences to the typical 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE7416ACE89EBBBFA882294" authorityName=", Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan" authorityYear="2010" box="[1231,1338,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hetrodini">Hetrodini</taxonomicName>
pattern.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE7416ACA81EB96FDD6235C" blockId="17.[151,1437,439,898]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE7416ACA81EB96FE8F2371" bold="true" box="[199,317,762,788]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Genitalia.</emphasis>
In a comparison of figures, the titillator of our specimen (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE7416AC980EB97FBAC2370" box="[966,1054,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1200,1224]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,237,1177]" captionTargetId="figure-41@13.[151,1436,237,1179]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Titillator and genitalic sclerites in Hetrodini, Enyaliopsina. First row A Cosmoderus femoralis (CH8627), B Enyaliopsis bloyeti (Kazimzumbwi), C Enyaliopsis carolinus (Minziro), D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus (Rau Forest); second row E Enyaliopsis spec. 1 near ephippiatus (Mwala), F Enyaliopsis jennae (Uluguru), G Enyaliopsis spec. 2 (Mpwapwa), H Enyaliopsis spec. 3 (East Chenene); third row I Gymnoproctus rammei (Puge Simbo), J Gymnoproctus spec. (East Chenene)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392735" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392735/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
) is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE7416ACF02EB97FEE8235C" authority="Glenn, 1991" authorityName="Glenn" authorityYear="1991" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Enyaliopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monsteri">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE7416ACF02EB97FF7B235D" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">E. monsteri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE7416ACA96EA73FEE8235C" author="Glenn, G. S. Jr." box="[208,346,799,825]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" pagination="67 - 102" refId="ref16270" refString="Glenn, G. S. Jr. (1991) A systematic revision of Enyaliopsis Karsch 1887 (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae, Hetrodinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 117, 67 - 102. http: // www. jstor. org / stable / 25078540" type="journal article" year="1991">Glenn, 1991</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE7416ACB8EEA73FDA6235D" box="[456,532,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">petersi</emphasis>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE7416ACA81EA2EFBDC23E4" blockId="17.[151,1437,439,898]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE7416ACA81EA2EFEC92339" bold="true" box="[199,379,834,860]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468">Chromosomes:</emphasis>
2n = 27 (26 + X0), FN = 30; pair 1 submetacentric, 2–13 acrocentric, X chromosome metacentric (
<specimenCount id="41F9FD5DFFE7416ACA89EA0BFEAF23E7" box="[207,285,871,898]" pageId="17" pageNumber="468" type="male">1 male</specimenCount>
); thin C-bands in the paracentromeric region of all chromosomes (
